Virgil's “Gathering of the Clans”

It may be worth while also to look at xi. 390, because there the pause occurs in the middle of the impassioned rhetoric of Turnus against Drances, just to allow one bitter taunt to sink in, before he turns to take up another point of Drances' speech :

‘⁸ Imus in adversos—quid cessas? an tibi Mavors ventosa in lingua pedibusque fugacibus istis semper erit? pulsus ego? aut quisquam merito, foedissime, pulsum arguet. . . .”

Ι think I may fairly assume that anyone who examines these passages, to help him in judging of the one more particularly under consideration, will not fail to conclude that the second bird-simile is

absolutely inadmissible after the hemistich.
